He and the others were scared to do it, but one younger kid around 6 was brave and climbed to the top. The kid shouted at them that he could see a "lake monster" in the water that was watching some little boy there. Other kids thought he was making stuff up and continued playing.

There was an old /x/ greentext story that I still think about. The poster said when he was 7 years old he went on a trip to a local lake with his family. He was on a playground close to the lake in the area, playing with some other kids on a pretty tall "spider web" type climber.

... there that the adults around the area would be unable to physically. I think this has to do with what I've called the "qualitative aspects of space" and the climber serving as a symbolic vantage point or mountaintop. Vertical elevation allows for a lesser "omniscient" vision.

When the poster and his family were leaving they saw a police car and people around and found out a boy had drowned in the lake. A spider web climber is like 20 feet/6 meters tall. Pretty high, but not a bird eye's view. It's not like the 6 year old boy could see something up ...

Same as Christ and the devil on the mountain seeing all kingdoms of the world or experiences of dying people's souls ascending in the air and being able to see the entire city simultaneously, including everyone indoors, etc. The boy could see the situation literally "from above".

I assume this "qualitative aspect" of space is also why some tribes (per Sir James Frazer) have a "flood myth" where the only place above the waters is a local small hill or even an island even if there are other far higher mountains visible that the locals claim were underwater.

As in that small hilltop or river island near where the tribe lives acts as a similar "vantage point" to the playground spider web climber and is taller than it appears when physically measured in terms of quantitative space. The vertical elevation itself simply acts as a symbol.

I assume from the perspective of the six year old kid on top of the climber he was seeing the drowning boy and the lake monster in a direct and unmediated way, perceiving them to be somewhere below him, like how you would watch a valley below from a mountain. Not like "a vision".
